Oxygen toxicity

#2020SBR-JUL/Q01
Oxygen toxicity occurs because of hyperoxia (excess oxygen in tissues) and hyperoxaemia (excess oxygen in the blood).

[!INFO] Oxygen pressures
partial pressure of oxygen in room air at sea level is about 160 mmHg.
100% oxygen at sea level pressure will give a 'partial' pressure of 760 mmHg (= to Patm).
Partial pressure of inspired oxygen can be increased either by increasing FiO2 or increasing inspired gas pressure.
Deep sea divers (>180 ft) must inhale gasses with less than 21% oxygen to avoid toxicity.

In acute toxicity, CNS features predominate and in chronic toxicity, pumlonary features are more prevalent. Source

  • Lung injury :
    • Paranchymal lung injury through increases production of reactive oxygen species (ROS) -> all the way upto ARDS and diffuse alveolar damage.
    • Also causes absorption atelectasis, airway injury and worsening hypercapnia[[2020-NOV-GeneralMedicine|Oxygen in COPD]] and [[2021-SBR-JUL#^e8498e|Haldane effect]].
  • Extrapulmonary effects:
    • Local effects -> nasal dryness and increased risk of fire.
    • Cardiovascaular -> increased peripheral vascular resistace + decreased myocardial contractility => decreased cardiac output. (but whether this is clinically relevant in humans is not known).
    • CNS -> (Bert effect) hyperbaric oxygen increases risk of seizures.
      • Effects of CNS oxygen toxicity include twitching of perioral and small hand muscles.
      • Vertigo, nausea, altered behaviour, clumsiness, diziness
  • In neonates, retinopathy of prematurity and bronchopulmonary dysplasia.

[!INFO] CNS tolerance
"If a physician prescribes a one hour HBOT treatment at 2 ATA, the patient breathes 100 percent oxygen for one hour while at two times the atmospheric pressure at sea level." - Source

As seen from this graph, the CNS effects of oxygen at less than 2ATA are not siginificant.

Sinus arrhythmia

#2020SBR-NOV/Q03

  • When present, normally indicates good cardiovascular health.
  • Respiratory sinus arrhythmia
    • The heart rate is under tonic vagal inhibition.
    • During inspiration, stretch receptors send afferent signals in the vagi which inhibit the cardioinhibitory area in the medulla.
    • This causes decreased vagal tone during inspiration -> causes increased heart rate in inspiration
    • Vagal tone increased in expiration -> decreased heart rate in expiration.

Band 3 anion exchanger and acidosis

#2020SBR-NOV/Q05
Band 3 is an anion exchanger located in RBC membranes (it's the most prevalent protein in the RBC membrane) and the kidney.

Some forms of familial distal renal tubular acidosis arises from band-3 malfunction.

Myocardial oxygen consumption

O2 consumption is proportional to work per beat.

$$
\Large{Myocardial\space Work\space Per\space Beat = Stroke\space Volume \times MAP}
$$
Work is also proportional to wall tension and contractile state. (as MAP determines the wall tension)
$$
\Large{work \propto wall\space tension \times contractile\space state}
$$

For some reason, myocardial O2 consumption is increased more in pressure overload than in volume overload. I.e Angina is more common in Aortic stenosis than in aortic regurgitation.

Verapamil is a suitable alternative for adenosine if it it contraindicated.

First ones used therapeutically - Tolbutamide. - First generation. (Tolbutamide has the lowest hypoglycaemic risk)
Some studies say the natriuretic effect of SGLT-2 inhibitors is small. Sourceand Source (? ignore)

Thiazide diuretics bind to the chloride receptor of the Na-Cl cotransported in the DCT and inhibit it's function causing urinary loss of Sodium and Chloride.
(mnemonic: the part after the descent when writing the letter G)

  • Hyponatremia is rare
    These changes (except the lack of hyponatremia) are very similar to changes caused by chronic thiazide use. Thiazides and Gitelman affect the same transporter (NCCT)

Bartter syndrome

characterized by characterized by hypokalemia, hypochloremia, metabolic alkalosis, and hyperreninemia with normal blood pressure
Kidney abnormality causing excessive urinary off of sodium, chloride and pottasium.

Gitelman syndrome is a subset of Bartter syndrome.
THere are many variants of Bartter syndrome but classic Barttery syndrome is caused by mutaition of the basolateral chloride channel which is required for normal sodium chloride reabsorption.

ECG changes in hypokalemia

ECG changes in hyperkalemia :

#2020SBR-NOV/19
#2020SBR-JUL/Q02
The pathophysiology of changes in hyperkalemia includes

  • acceleration of terminal repolarization (causes T wave abnormalities)
  • Depression of conduction between adjacent myocytes -> Prolongation of PR and QRS duration. Source

    Boradening of the QRS complex is a feature (although not mentioned in the table below) Source
    | Level | Changes | Basis |
    | --------- | ------------------------------------------------------------ | -------------------------------- |
    | 5.5 - 6.5 |📑 Tall t waves | Repolarization abnormalities |
    | 6.5 - 7 | 📑 P wave widening and flattening, broadening of PR interval | Progressive atrial paralysis |
    | 7.0 - 9.0 |📑 Sinus brady, AV block, AF, conduction blocks | Conduction abnormalities |
    | > 9.0 | Sine wave | Peri arrest |
    In hyperkalemia, ECG changes progress from peaked T-waves to widened QRS and eventually to ventricular tachycardia, fibrillation or pulseless electrical activity arrest.  These progressive changes can correlate with rising potassium levels. For example, peaked T waves might correspond with a potassium level of approximately 6 mmol/L, whereas cardiac arrest generally occurs at higher levels.

Hypokalemia

[!INFO] Mnemonic: Opposite of the hyperkalemic changes

EKG changes can include

  • increased amplitude and width of P wave,
  • T wave flattening and inversion,
  • prominent U waves and
  • apparent long QT intervals due to merging of the T and U wave and
  • 'mild' ST depression.

The 'classic findings' are

  • Diminished T wave, increased U wave, ST depression Source

The U-wave is a deflection following the T wave. . Potassium levels that are critically low (<1.7 mmol/L) can lead to torsades de pointes or “twisting of the points”, a polymorphic ventricular tachycardia.

[!INFO] 📑U wave

  • Best seen in V2 and V3.

Torsades de Poites

  • Life threatening arrhtymia
  • QRS morphology changes from beat to beat.
  • Associated with acquired or congenital prolonged QT
  • Can occur in hypokaemia
  • Group Ia antiarrthmics which prolong QT should never be used! (basically, dysopyramide is contraindicated) [[Cardiology MCQ discussion#Antiarrhythmic drugs|Antiarrhtymics]]

Hyponatremia and hypernatremia have no effect on the ECG.

Increased (hypernatremia) and decreased (hyponatremia) sodium levels do not have any effect on the ECG, nor cardiac rhythm, or impulse conduction. Source

#2020SBR-NOV/Q03
Overall effects : increased contractile velocity (increased contractility) and decreased heart rate.

1️⃣ Heart failure - inhibition of Na/K ATPase -> increased intra-myocyte sodium -> decreased Na calcium exchange -> reduced secretion of calcium -> increased intracellular calcium -> contractility increased.

  • However, elevated intracellular calcium also increases risk of arrhythmias.

  • Increased parasympathetic tone to the SA node and AV node -> (via hypersensitization of carotid sinus baroreceptors, central stimulation, increased vagal output, and possible potentiation of the effect of acetylcholine on the sinoatrial [SA] node) -> slowing the firing of the SA node and prolonging conduction at the atrioventricular (AV) node.

  • supratherapeutic doses can cause sinus brady, AV block, arrhythmias

[!INFO] At normal pCO2, O2 has little effect on respiratory drive but as soon as PCO2 increases, PO2 begins to have a much larger effect

#2020SBR-JUL/Q01
📑 PO2 based resiratory drive overrides the above two factors when PO2 drops to 'dangerously' low levels (i.e PaO2 approx 60.)

📑Above Pao2 of 80 mm Hg, O2 has little effect on respiratory drive
